<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="growth-seo-link-building">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>seo-manager</domain>
    <summary>Value-first link building: create genuinely link-worthy content, identify who would link and why, conduct personalized outreach, and measure results iteratively.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>link-building</tag>
      <tag>seo</tag>
      <tag>backlinks</tag>
      <tag>outreach</tag>
      <tag>content</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>SEO Link Building</title>
    <summary>A value-first link building methodology: create genuinely link-worthy content, identify who would link and why, conduct personalized outreach, and measure results iteratively. Covers content types with high link potential, prospecting methods (competitor analysis, resource pages, broken links, HARO), outreach templates, and tracking.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Backlinks remain a primary Google ranking signal. Sites with quality inbound links from relevant, authoritative domains rank higher and build domain authority over time. Black-hat tactics (buying links, PBNs) risk manual penalties; the value-first approach produces sustainable rankings by earning links through content quality and relationship building.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Site has good content but low organic visibility due to lack of backlinks</item>
        <item>Starting a link building campaign for a specific asset (guide, tool, research)</item>
        <item>Setting up a repeatable outreach process for ongoing link acquisition</item>
        <item>Analyzing competitor backlink profiles to find gaps and opportunities</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Site has critical technical SEO issues — fix those first before building links</item>
        <item>Content quality is thin — links won't help if the asset isn't link-worthy</item>
        <item>Domain is brand new (under 3 months) — focus on technical foundation first</item>
        <item>Expecting results within days — link building has a 3-6 month ranking lag</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="content-types-by-link-potential">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Create content that journalists and bloggers need but that doesn't yet exist or is outdated — this is the only reliably scalable link magnet formula.</statement>
        <rationale>Generic content earns generic results. Link magnets are assets people reference repeatedly: original data, free tools, comprehensive guides, industry benchmarks. Without a genuinely link-worthy asset, outreach volume cannot compensate.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Original research / surveys: Very High link potential</item>
        <item>Free interactive tools / calculators: Very High link potential</item>
        <item>Industry benchmarks with data: Very High link potential</item>
        <item>Ultimate / comprehensive guides: High link potential</item>
        <item>Expert roundups: Medium link potential</item>
        <item>Case studies with real data: Medium link potential</item>
        <item>Original graphics / infographics: Medium link potential</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="prospecting-methods">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Build a prospect list of 100+ sites before starting outreach — quality and volume both matter.</statement>
        <rationale>Response rates average 10-20%; link acquisition rate averages 5-10%. Starting with fewer than 100 prospects produces statistically insignificant results and cannot reveal which tactics work.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Competitor backlink analysis (Ahrefs): who links to competing content</item>
        <item>Resource page search: "[topic] + resources" / "[topic] + useful links"</item>
        <item>Broken link building: find broken links, offer replacement</item>
        <item>HARO / Qwoted: respond to journalist queries (High quality, inbound)</item>
        <item>Unlinked brand mentions: find mentions without links, request attribution</item>
        <item>Skyscraper technique: find linked content, create superior version</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="outreach-principles">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Personalize every outreach email — generic emails are ignored at rates above 90%.</statement>
        <rationale>Outreach recipients receive dozens of generic link requests daily. A personalized first line referencing specific content they published signals genuine effort and increases response rates from ~2% (generic) to ~15-20% (personalized).</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Follow up exactly once, 7 days after the initial send — never follow up more than once.</statement>
        <rationale>A single follow-up recovers responses from busy recipients who missed the first email. Multiple follow-ups damage relationship and sender reputation without proportional benefit.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Send volume: 50 emails per day maximum to protect sender reputation</item>
        <item>Personalization: read 2-3 recent articles, reference specific content in first line</item>
        <item>Value framing: explain why linking benefits THEIR audience, not just you</item>
        <item>Easy ask: provide direct link, short description, specific reason to include</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="internal-linking">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Audit internal links monthly: link new posts to relevant old content, update old posts to link to new content, build pillar-cluster structures with keyword-rich anchors.</statement>
        <rationale>Internal links are the highest-ROI link building tactic — zero outreach effort, immediate implementation, direct PageRank distribution, and visible ranking improvements within weeks not months.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="target-metrics">
      <list>
        <item>Response rate: 10% = good, 20%+ = great</item>
        <item>Link acquisition rate: 5% = good, 10%+ = great</item>
        <item>Average DR of new links: 40+ = good, 60+ = great</item>
        <item>New referring domains per month: 5+ = good, 20+ = great</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Buying links or using private blog networks (PBNs)</description>
      <reason>Google manual and algorithmic penalties — site-wide ranking loss that can take months to recover from. The short-term ranking boost is not worth the existential risk.</reason>
    </antipattern>
    <antipattern>
      <description>Sending generic outreach at scale without personalization</description>
      <reason>Response rates drop below 2%, burning prospect lists and sender domain reputation simultaneously.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <checklist>
      <check>Phase 1: Audit existing content for link-worthiness</check>
      <check>Phase 1: Identify 3-5 potential link magnet assets</check>
      <check>Phase 1: Document current backlinks (Ahrefs or Moz baseline)</check>
      <check>Phase 1: Analyze competitor backlink profiles</check>
      <check>Phase 1: Set up tracking: Ahrefs/Moz account, Hunter.io, link tracking spreadsheet</check>
      <check>Phase 1: Set link acquisition target (number of links per month)</check>
      <check>Phase 2: Create or update link magnet asset (research, tool, guide, data)</check>
      <check>Phase 2: Ensure comprehensive unique value — not a rewrite of existing content</check>
      <check>Phase 2: Add visuals: charts, infographics, embeddable data</check>
      <check>Phase 2: Write 1-2 paragraph asset description for outreach use</check>
      <check>Phase 2: Create key statistics / findings summary</check>
      <check>Phase 2: Prepare social media graphics for promotion</check>
      <check>Phase 3: Export competitor backlinks from Ahrefs, filter by DR 40+</check>
      <check>Phase 3: Search "[topic] + resources" and "[topic] + useful links" for resource pages</check>
      <check>Phase 3: Use Ahrefs broken link tool on high-DA niche pages</check>
      <check>Phase 3: Sign up for HARO / Qwoted and monitor daily queries</check>
      <check>Phase 3: Build master prospect list of 100+ sites</check>
      <check>Phase 3: Segment by opportunity type and domain authority</check>
      <check>Phase 3: Find contact information for each prospect (Hunter.io, LinkedIn)</check>
      <check>Phase 4: Read 2-3 recent articles per prospect for personalization material</check>
      <check>Phase 4: Write 2-3 outreach template variants (resource page, broken link, guest post)</check>
      <check>Phase 4: Personalize first line for each email</check>
      <check>Phase 4: Send in batches of 50/day maximum</check>
      <check>Phase 4: Log all sends in tracking spreadsheet</check>
      <check>Phase 4: Respond to all replies within 24 hours</check>
      <check>Phase 4: Send one follow-up after 7 days of no response</check>
      <check>Phase 5: Monitor new backlinks daily (first week of campaign)</check>
      <check>Phase 5: Record: domain, DR, dofollow/nofollow, anchor text</check>
      <check>Phase 5: Calculate response rate and link acquisition rate</check>
      <check>Phase 5: Identify which templates and prospect types had highest conversion</check>
      <check>Phase 5: Double down on best-performing tactics</check>
      <check>Phase 5: Create SOP for future campaigns from learnings</check>
      <check>Ongoing: Maintain 20-50 outreach emails per month minimum</check>
      <check>Ongoing: Create linkable assets quarterly</check>
      <check>Ongoing: Audit internal links: new to old, old to new, orphan pages</check>
      <check>Ongoing: Monitor competitor link activity</check>
      <check>Ongoing: Report: new referring domains, DR distribution, ranking changes</check>
    </checklist>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/campaign-tracker.md" purpose="Link building campaign tracking template with metrics"/>
      <template path="templates/outreach-templates.txt" purpose="Personalized outreach email templates (resource page, broken link, guest post)"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
